li.p:
Remember that at least one of three conditions must fail:
if the function lacks a limit,
if the function is undefined,
or if the limit exists but does not equal the function value,
then f is not continuous at the point.

Based on our work in (a), (b), and (c),
f is not continuous at a=-2 and a = 2 because f does not have a limit at those points;
f is not continuous at a = 3 since f is not defined there;
and f is not continuous at a = -1 because at that point its limit does not equal its function value.
